<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-12-09T12:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-12-09T12:00:00-05:00" n="378" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d378">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 658.119/724</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Great Britain</hi> (<persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_LIB1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Laughlin</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                </hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-12-09T17:00:00+00:00">
                                        <hi rend="italic">December 9, 1918, 5 p.m.</hi>
                                    </date>
                                    <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 6.30 p.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>4446. War Trade Board [from <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_SLP1">Sheldon</persName>]:</p>
                            <p>No. 2032. Your 1774, Department’s 3225, December 4, 8 p.m. I note as
                                per last paragraph that you are sending copies of letters to the
                                British and French Embassies which furnish details with reference to
                                American participation in the purchase of molybdenum from Norway and
                                iron ore from Sweden. In your 1502, Department’s 2440, October 25
                                    [<hi rend="italic">26</hi>], last sentence, you stated that you
                                were preparing a plan for handling resales of Swedish ore which you
                                would submit to me shortly. I have never received this and pending
                                its arrival I have never executed any agreement authorized in your
                                1444, Department’s 2079 [<hi rend="italic">2279</hi>], October 18.
                                If the letters exchanged between you and the British and French
                                Embassies have not concretely covered our engagement concerning the
                                purchase of Swedish ores and the plan for handling resales, please
                                send me the plan for resales mentioned in your 1502 so that the
                                whole matter may be arranged without further delay.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_LIB1">
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Laughlin</hi>
                                    </persName>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>